@tmatsuo didn't explain *why* we had to suppress any unnecessary API calls... He just said "please do it". I'd like to know where that's coming from, considering I'd like to hit the API when retrieving a topic so I know whether it exists or not... 

Boto in s3 (as a separate example) does this, and has a "validate" keyword that says "don't make an API call" (the default is "please make the API call"). For example

```python
bucket = conn.get_bucket('name')  # API request
bucket = conn.get_bucket('name', validate=False)  # No API request
```

In the search API draft I have, I just called this "check", but the pattern is similar: https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/gcloud-python/pull/892/files#diff-056d3999e591db310404f19fbf639531R105

For comparison, gcloud-node let's you instantiate this (almost) the same way:

```javascript
// Create a new topic:
pubsub.createTopic('name', function(err, topic) {
  // Do something with the topic
});

// Get a topic that may or may not exist:
var topic = pubsub.topic('name', {autoCreate: true});
// Do something with topic.

// Delete an existing topic:
var topic = pubsub.topic('name');
topic.delete();

```

