1.
> If we do copy everything over and refuse to add a redirect when one exists in either the HTTP or HTTPS server block, while we leave a lot of unnecessary stuff in their server block, I'm unaware of any possibilities of incorrect behavior from nginx here. It seems like even if we leave things like SSL directives in the block, Nginx just ignores them.

Yes, that's what happens.

2. Your example wouldn't actually cause a redirect loop.

Let's say they had:
```
server {
  server_name example.org www.example.org;
  if ($host = "example.org") {
      return 301 http://www.example.org$request_uri;
  }
}
```
Then, we deploy:
```
server {
  server_name example.org www.example.org;
  if ($host = "example.org") {
      return 301 http://www.example.org$request_uri;
  }
  listen 80;
  listen 443 ssl; etc.
}
```
Now we add a redirect for example.org:
```
server {
  server_name example.org www.example.org;
  listen 80;
  return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
}
server {
  server_name example.org www.example.org;
  if ($host = "example.org") {
      return 301 http://www.example.org$request_uri;
  }
  listen 443 ssl; etc.
}
```
Now we add a redirect for www.example.org:
```
server {
  server_name example.org www.example.org;
  listen 80;
  return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
}
server {
  server_name example.org www.example.org;
  listen 80;
  return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
}
server {
  server_name example.org www.example.org;
  if ($host = "example.org") {
      return 301 http://www.example.org$request_uri;
  }
  listen 443 ssl; etc.
}
```
(I admit that this is superfluous, and we should in fact be just putting the single requested server_name per newly created server block.)
This isn't a redirect loop. If you request example.org, it tells you to go to http://www.example.org, so you do, and that tells you to go to https://www.example.org. No problem here.

The only way it would cause a loop is if it there's a redirect from https to http in there with nothing else changed, which is not a thing that happens. That's why I decided to only keep those directives in the first place.

I don't think we should refuse to do this if there's a redirect in the existing server block. The nice thing about doing it the way I have implemented is it allows us to put in the https redirect for the common case illustrated above.

Even for the logs, they'll still get all the previous functionality when the request arrives on 443 one redirect later. If they want more reporting or fancier things to happen when 80 comes in, they can add those manually. This is the safest way that allows us to handle most of the cases.

Looks like we're not using the `n=16` parameter. Also, is there a specific reason why we're using an explicit namespace instead of simply using `uuid4` for example? We could simplify this function a bit:
```
def random_id():
    return str(uuid.uuid4())
```
(or even remove this function and use the value directly in line 135).
